  },
  {
    q: 'What is GEO (Generative Engine Optimization)?',
    a: 'GEO is the emerging discipline of optimizing web content for citation by AI search engines — ChatGPT, Claude, Perplexity, Gemini, You.com. It overlaps with SEO but has distinct signals: llms.txt adoption, stable permalinks, canonical Q&A structure, rich JSON-LD schema, and clear citation formatting. PointCast\'s /agent-native pillar is a working reference for GEO implementation.',
  },
  {
    q: 'What is llms.txt and should my site have one?',
    a: 'llms.txt (proposed by Jeremy Howard, September 2024) is a root-path Markdown file that gives LLMs a curated index of your site. ~10% of sites had adopted it by early 2026 — Anthropic, Stripe, Cloudflare, Vercel, and Perplexity ship one. If your content is worth citing, yes: it takes 15 minutes to write and compounds every time an LLM crawls. See /agent-native for PointCast\'s implementation.',
  },
  {
    q: 'Which AI tools does PointCast use daily?',
    a: 'Daily-tier: Claude (Opus 4.7, via web + Claude Code CLI), ChatGPT (for cross-checks and voice), Cursor (IDE-embedded autocomplete for occasional quick edits), Perplexity (web search with citations). Weekly-tier: ChatGPT voice mode, Gemini for very long documents. Occasional: Midjourney, Sora, Ideogram for image generation. See /ai-stack for all 24 tools with Mike\'s opinionated take on each.',
  },
  {
    q: 'How do I set up a human-AI collaboration workflow?',
    a: 'PointCast\'s pattern: one human (Mike) as director and editor, one primary engineer (Claude Code) running on hourly cron against a docs/inbox queue, one repo-scoped specialist (Codex via MCP), one ops agent (Manus). The human writes briefs, reviews commits, and makes strategic calls. The agents ship sprints autonomously between human sessions. Full session logs at /sprints; collaborator registry at /collabs.',
  },
  {
    q: 'What is Model Context Protocol (MCP)?',
    a: 'MCP is Anthropic\'s open protocol for connecting AI models to external tools and data sources. PointCast ships an MCP server card at /.well-known/mcp/server-card.json and exposes block data, collaborators, and recent ships through MCP-compatible endpoints. Any MCP-speaking agent (Claude Desktop, custom clients) can query PointCast via the protocol.',
